[1] Nigeria
Date: Thu 14 Sep 2017
Source: Independent Nigeria [edited]
http://independent.ng/measles-33m-nigerian-children-to-be-vaccinated-says-nphcda-boss/


The Executive Secretary, Primary Healthcare Development Agency (NPHCDA), Dr Faisal Shuaib said about 33 million eligible Nigerian children are targeted to be immunized during the 2017/2018 measles vaccine campaign.

He made this known while addressing journalists at a one day media orientation forum for the 2017/2018 measles campaign organised by NPHCDA in Abuja.

Shuaib who was represented at the event by the Director of Advocacy and Communication, Dr Eugene Orvihi-Ivase, stated that this year's [2017] campaign is targeting over 31 million (95 percent) of the 33 million eligible children.

According to him, "There is no way we would stop immunization campaigns, except we are able to immunize 31 million out of the 33 million eligible children from 9 months to 5 years old."

He recalled that, "By August 2017 or the 32nd week of 2017, there are 16 348 suspected cases of measles in Nigeria and 108 laboratory confirmed cases affecting all states and virtually all local governments."

According to him, "We are assuring Nigerians that we will deploy the necessary tools to ensure the campaign is successful."

He stressed that the main objective of the campaign is to reduce the occurrence of measles and deaths due to the disease and outbreaks in the country.

"Children born after the last measles campaign from 2013 to 2016 and who have never received routine immunization are now more at risk of the disease.

"Immunization is the most effective way to protect your children against measles and other diseases that vaccines can prevent. We must prevent our children dying of measles."

The NPHCDA boss said all hands must be on desk to mobilize mothers to bring their children for measles immunization. And the vaccination is 100 percent free. He appealed to those states that are yet to release their counterpart funds to do so.

He said that measles is a highly contagious disease that is caused by a virus and that it affects mostly children. It is one of the leading causes of death among young children. It spreads very quickly from child to child. A child who contracts measles can have reduced ability to fight other diseases, resulting in frequent illnesses.

The measles vaccine campaign is expected to last from 26 Oct 2017 to March 2018.

[Byline: Toyin Adebayo]

