[5] Australia (New South Wales)
Date: Sun 17 Sep 2017 4:00 PM AEST
Source: Manly Daily/Daily Telegraph [edited] http://tinyurl.com/yd8bvw5b


In 2014, Australia was declared measles-free, but this viral infection that can pose a serious health risk for small children is back.

Following a global trend, NSW [New South Wales] has seen an increase in measles this year [2017], with 23 cases reported, including 7 of those in children aged under 5 years.

Immunisation research specialist Professor Robert Booy, from The Children's Hospital at Westmead, says the jump in measles cases is a reminder of the importance of immunisation.

"The best way to prevent measles is to get vaccinated," Prof Booy says.

The 1st major outbreak of measles in Sydney in 3 years hit in April this year [2017]. It was introduced by a traveller who contracted it in Bali, but it quickly spread in western Sydney, with 10 cases reported in the Auburn and Bankstown LGAs [local government areas] in one week.

Prof Booy says measles is usually spread when a person breathes in the virus that has been coughed or sneezed into the air by an infectious person. Measles is one of our most contagious viruses, just being in the same room as someone can result in infection.

"The 1st symptoms of the illness are fever, tiredness, runny nose, sore red eyes, conjunctivitis, and a cough," Prof Booy says. "A few days later, a rash appears. The rash starts on the face, spreads down to the body, and lasts 4-7 days."

Up to 1/3rd of people with measles have complications, including ear infections, diarrhoea, and pneumonia, and may require hospitalisation.

NSW Health reports that 1 in every 1000 people with measles develops encephalitis (swelling of the brain).

All children and adults born during or after 1966 should be vaccinated with 2 doses of measles containing vaccine if not already immune.

The MMR (measles, mumps, and rubella) vaccine is recommended at 12 months, with the 2nd dose, which now includes varicella (MMRV), at 18 months.

- Measles is a serious disease that is easily spread through the air;
- measles is now rare in NSW because of immunisation;
- people with measles are usually infectious from just before the symptoms begin until 4 days after the rash appears;
- the time from exposure to becoming sick is usually about 10 days. The rash usually appears around 14 days after exposure.

[Byline: Raylene Bliss]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
