[6] Australia (Victoria, New South Wales)
Date: Tue 19 Sep 2017
Source: Bendigo Advertiser [edited]
http://www.bendigoadvertiser.com.au/story/4932536/measles-alert-three-cases-confirmed-in-victoria/?cs=3329


Two confirmed cases of measles in Melbourne have been discovered in the past week, sparking a warning to doctors and hospitals from Victoria's chief health officer.

One person acquired the illness in Melbourne, and the 2nd may have been infected locally or overseas.

A 3rd case of measles was confirmed late on Mon [18 Sep 2017] night. The Health Department said the 3rd person contracted the measles overseas, but at this stage, they believe it is not related to the other 2 cases.

As the source of the infection is unknown, the Health Department has warned that there may already be secondary cases in the community that have not been diagnosed.

Measles is highly infectious and airborne, and can stay in the environment for up to 2 hours. It has an incubation period of between 7 and 18 days. ...

Symptoms of the measles include a general rash lasting 3 or more days and fever (at least 38C [100 F]) with the onset of the rash, and a cough, blocked nose, or conjunctivitis.

Anyone who presents with symptoms compatible with measles should be tested and notified to the department.

The latest cases take Victoria's total notifications of measles to 12 this year [2017], down from 37 this time last year.

[Byline: Marika Dobbin-Thomas]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail from HealthMap Alerts
<promed@promedmail.org>

[While this report states that the number of measles cases in Victoria, 12, is lower this year [2017], down from 37 this time last year, it is interesting that the previous report observed that New South Wales has seen an increase in measles this year, with 23 cases reported, including 7 of those in children aged under 5 years. The outbreaks are likely focal due to introduction from a traveler, leading to disparate incidences in different locations. - Mod.LK]
